VERDICT: confirmed-but-no-uca
REASON: Drift reproduces on HEAD by direct inspection of the cited FFI functions. gale_spinlock_acquire (ffi/src/lib.rs:9880-9896) checks only owner_tid != 0, so a call with owner_tid=0, new_tid=0 takes the success path, writes *out_owner=0 and *out_nest_count=1, and returns 0 — producing the ambiguous post-state (owner=0, nest=1). gale_spinlock_acquire_check(0) then returns 1 (line 9862-9866, "free"), violating SL1 because a verified-model state with nest_count=1 is reported acquirable; gale_spinlock_release(0, 1, 0, ...) short-circuits on `owner_tid == 0 || owner_tid != tid` (line 9957) and returns -EPERM, violating SL2/SL4 — the rightful holder cannot release. The Verus proof in src/spinlock.rs (lines 112-276, inv line 61-68) operates on Option<u32> and quantifies over all u32 including 0; the FFI injection None↦0, Some(t)↦t is non-injective at t=0. Every Kani harness in ffi/src/lib.rs:9988-10043 carries kani::assume(tid != 0), explicitly masking the failing region. The Oracle (sl_drift_tid_zero with the assume removed) and the PoC (spinlock_tid_zero_poc) both fire on unfixed code by construction. Interestingness: no documented precondition requires tid != 0 (neither in src/spinlock.rs doc comments, the FFI doc comments, nor zephyr/gale_spinlock.c); Verus claims universal u32 coverage; Zephyr's pointer-derived _current is incidentally nonzero but the report correctly flags this as latent, not specified. Not covered in docs/safety or a known-limitation list. No UCA exists to map to: artifacts/stpa.yaml contains only hazards H-1..H-6 and system-constraints SC-1..SC-6 and explicitly states "Control structure, UCAs, and loss scenarios are out of scope for this initial artifact"; safety/stpa/ucas.yaml does not exist in the repository. The closest hazards are H-4 (deadlock → L-3, matches SL2/SL4 permanent-stuck consequence) and a missing mutual-exclusion hazard (SL1 violation would feed L-1/L-2). Recommend a new SL-UCA-1 ("spinlock ownership encoding collapses Some(0) onto None; acquire/release succeed/fail in states that violate SL1/SL2/SL4") grouped under a future synchronization-primitive UCA block, with links prevents→(new mutual-exclusion hazard) and leads-to-loss→L-1/L-3.
